# Notebook Blank Edit — first edit per Agent interaction

## MANDATORY — read before any `.ipynb` cell-body change

**This file is `alwaysApply: true`.** It is part of every Agent turn. **Follow it; do not “summarize it away.”**

**Project policy:** The user **accepts or rejects** notebook edits using Cursor’s **per-cell red/green diff**. Edits that **auto-apply without** that UI are **unacceptable** for production notebooks.

- **Burn slot first** — sacrificial first `EditNotebook` so a “lost” diff hits throwaway content (see below).
- **One substantive `EditNotebook` per assistant reply, per notebook file** — after the burn: **at most one** additional `EditNotebook` on that `.ipynb` in the same reply. For more cells, **stop**; the user sends another message (e.g. “continue”) and you run **burn again** (new user message = new obligation) then the next single edit. **Exception:** the user **explicitly** approves a batch for a named scope (“apply all markdown headers in one go,” etc.).
- If anything conflicts with speed or convenience, **review visibility wins** unless the user waived batching in writing in that thread.

**Also read:** `.cursor/rules/jupyter-notebook-workflow.mdc` for `540_tenure_pipeline.ipynb` (burn at **index 3**) and same-cell merge rules.

---

## What counts as a new obligation (“interaction”)

For this rule, **one interaction** = **one user message** submitted in the **Agent** chat (each time you type something and press Enter to send).

- A new user message **starts a fresh obligation**: if you will edit any `.ipynb` in that reply, the burn-slot edit comes **first** for that file (see below).
- Reads, search, MCP **read/outline** (no cell-body change) **do not** satisfy or replace the burn edit; they can happen before it.
- **Once per notebook file per interaction**:
  1. The **first** `EditNotebook` on that file **must** be **only** the burn — no other cell in that call.
  2. The **second** `EditNotebook` on that file (if any) is the **single** allowed substantive edit for that file in that reply (one cell created/changed, with all line changes to **that** cell merged into **one** `old_string`/`new_string` per `jupyter-notebook-workflow.mdc`).
  3. **No third, fourth, …** substantive `EditNotebook` on the same file in the same reply unless the user **explicitly** approved batching.

**Why one substantive edit:** In practice, **chaining** many `EditNotebook` calls in one assistant turn often results in **only the first** showing a proper accept/reject diff; later edits may **apply silently**. The burn absorbs the first “invisible” hit; **capping at one real edit per turn** keeps each change **reviewable**.

If the agent will **not** use `EditNotebook` on any notebook in that reply, **no** burn edit is required.

## One-time exception — brand-new `.ipynb`

When **creating a notebook from scratch** at the user’s request, it is acceptable to use **notebook MCP** for **`notebook_create`** and a **single** initial scaffold (e.g. one `notebook_bulk_add_cells` pass: title, **EDIT BLANK** burn cell at index 1, and minimal placeholder cells only). That avoids an empty file with no burn slot.

**After that bootstrap file exists, the exception ends.** Every later change to **cell bodies** or **new substantive cells** must follow:

1. **`EditNotebook`** visible blank edit on the burn cell (see below).
2. **`EditNotebook`** for **exactly one** substantive change **per assistant reply** (unless the user explicitly approved batching for this task).
3. Further changes: wait for the **next user message**, then repeat from (1).

Do **not** use **`notebook_add_cell`**, **`notebook_bulk_add_cells`**, or **`notebook_edit_cell`** to inject real code or markdown after bootstrap unless the user explicitly approved that structural path for that step.

For **`540_tenure_pipeline.ipynb`**, use burn slot at **cell index 3** and follow **`.cursor/rules/jupyter-notebook-workflow.mdc`** (not index 1).

